  <section id=3D"built-in-types">
<span id=3D"bltin-types"></span><h1>Built-in Types<a class=3D"headerlink" h=
ref=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#built-in-types" titl=
e=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h1>
<p>The following sections describe the standard types that are built into t=
he
interpreter.</p>
<p id=3D"index-0">The principal built-in types are numerics, sequences, map=
pings, classes,
instances and exceptions.</p>
<p>Some collection classes are mutable.  The methods that add, subtract, or
rearrange their members in place, and don=E2=80=99t return a specific item,=
 never return
the collection instance itself but <code class=3D"docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span></code>.</p>
<p>Some operations are supported by several object types; in particular,
practically all objects can be compared for equality, tested for truth
value, and converted to a string (with the <a class=3D"reference internal" =
href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#repr" title=3D"rep=
r"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">repr()</span></code></a> function or the
slightly different <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyt=
hon.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py p=
y-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str()</span></code=
></a> function).  The latter function is implicitly
used when an object is written by the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#print" title=3D"print"=
><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">print()</span></code></a> function.</p>
<section id=3D"truth-value-testing">
<span id=3D"truth"></span><h2>Truth Value Testing<a class=3D"headerlink" hr=
ef=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#truth-value-testing" =
title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-1">Any object can be tested for truth value, for use in an <=
a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/=
compound_stmts.html#if"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils litera=
l notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">if</span></code></a> or
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/compound_stmts.html#while"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils li=
teral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">while</span></code></a> condition or=
 as operand of the Boolean operations below.</p>
<p id=3D"index-2">By default, an object is considered true unless its class=
 defines either a
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#object.__bool__" title=3D"object.__bool__"><code class=3D"x=
ref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__bool__()=
</span></code></a> method that returns <code class=3D"docutils literal notr=
anslate"><span class=3D"pre">False</span></code> or a
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#object.__len__" title=3D"object.__len__"><code class=3D"xre=
f py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__len__()</s=
pan></code></a> method that
returns zero, when called with the object. <a class=3D"footnote-reference b=
rackets" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#id12" id=
=3D"id1" role=3D"doc-noteref"><span class=3D"fn-bracket">[</span>1<span cla=
ss=3D"fn-bracket">]</span></a> If one of the methods raises an
exception when called, the exception is propagated and the object does
not have a truth value (for example, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented" title=
=3D"NotImplemented"><code class=3D"xref py py-data docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">NotImplemented</span></code></a>).
Here are most of the built-in objects considered false:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple" id=3D"index-3">
<li><p>constants defined to be false: <code class=3D"docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">False</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>zero of any numeric type: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">0</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal not=
ranslate"><span class=3D"pre">0.0</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils li=
teral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">0j</span></code>, <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Decimal(0)</span></code>,
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Fraction(0=
,</span> <span class=3D"pre">1)</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>empty sequences and collections: <code class=3D"docutils literal not=
ranslate"><span class=3D"pre">''</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils lit=
eral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">()</span></code>, <code class=3D"docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">[]</span></code>, <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">{}</span></code>, <co=
de class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">set()</span><=
/code>,
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">range(0)</=
span></code></p></li>
</ul>
<p id=3D"index-4">Operations and built-in functions that have a Boolean res=
ult always return <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">0</span></code>
or <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">False</=
span></code> for false and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">1</span></code> or <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">True</span></code> for true, unless otherwise sta=
ted.
(Important exception: the Boolean operations <code class=3D"docutils litera=
l notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">or</span></code> and <code class=3D"docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">and</span></code> always retu=
rn
one of their operands.)</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"boolean-operations-and-or-not">
<span id=3D"boolean"></span><h2>Boolean Operations =E2=80=94 <code class=3D=
"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">and=
</span></code>, <code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notran=
slate"><span class=3D"pre">or</span></code>, <code class=3D"xref std std-ke=
yword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">not</span></code><a=
 class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.ht=
ml#boolean-operations-and-or-not" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a>=
</h2>
<p id=3D"index-5">These are the Boolean operations, ordered by ascending pr=
iority:</p>
<div class=3D"responsive-table__container"><table class=3D"docutils align-d=
efault">
<thead>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><th class=3D"head"><p>Operation</p></th>
<th class=3D"head"><p>Result</p></th>
<th class=3D"head"><p>Notes</p></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">or</span> <span class=3D"p=
re">y</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>if <em>x</em> is true, then <em>x</em>, else
<em>y</em></p></td>
<td><p>(1)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">and</span> <span class=3D"p=
re">y</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>if <em>x</em> is false, then <em>x</em>, else
<em>y</em></p></td>
<td><p>(2)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">not</span> <span class=3D"pre">x</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>if <em>x</em> is false, then <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">True</span></code>,
else <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">False=
</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>(3)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p id=3D"index-6">Notes:</p>
<ol class=3D"arabic simple">
<li><p>This is a short-circuit operator, so it only evaluates the second
argument if the first one is false.</p></li>
<li><p>This is a short-circuit operator, so it only evaluates the second
argument if the first one is true.</p></li>
<li><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">not=
</span></code> has a lower priority than non-Boolean operators, so <code cl=
ass=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">not</span> <span c=
lass=3D"pre">a</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre"=
>b</span></code> is
interpreted as <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"=
pre">not</span> <span class=3D"pre">(a</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</s=
pan> <span class=3D"pre">b)</span></code>, and <code class=3D"docutils lite=
ral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">a</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</s=
pan> <span class=3D"pre">not</span> <span class=3D"pre">b</span></code> is =
a syntax error.</p></li>
</ol>
</section>
<section id=3D"comparisons">
<span id=3D"stdcomparisons"></span><h2>Comparisons<a class=3D"headerlink" h=
ref=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#comparisons" title=
=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-7">There are eight comparison operations in Python.  They al=
l have the same
priority (which is higher than that of the Boolean operations).  Comparison=
s can
be chained arbitrarily; for example, <code class=3D"docutils literal notran=
slate"><span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span c=
lass=3D"pre">y</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre=
">z</span></code> is equivalent to <code class=3D"docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"pre">y</span> <span class=3D"pre">and</span>
<span class=3D"pre">y</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">z</span></code>, except that <em>y</em> is evaluated only once (bu=
t in both cases <em>z</em> is not
evaluated at all when <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span class=3D"pre">y<=
/span></code> is found to be false).</p>
<p>This table summarizes the comparison operations:</p>
<div class=3D"responsive-table__container"><table class=3D"docutils align-d=
efault">
<thead>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><th class=3D"head"><p>Operation</p></th>
<th class=3D"head"><p>Meaning</p></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>strictly less than</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>less than or equal</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">&gt;</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>strictly greater than</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">&gt;=3D</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>greater than or equal</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>equal</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">!=3D</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>not equal</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-even"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">is</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>object identity</p></td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"row-odd"><td><p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">is</span> <span class=3D"pre">not</span></code></p></td>
<td><p>negated object identity</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p id=3D"index-8">Unless stated otherwise, objects of different types never=
 compare equal.
The <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=3D=3D=
</span></code> operator is always defined but for some object types (for ex=
ample,
class objects) is equivalent to <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"htt=
ps://docs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#is"><code class=3D"xref s=
td std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">is</span><=
/code></a>. The <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D=
"pre">&lt;</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><spa=
n class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notr=
anslate"><span class=3D"pre">&gt;</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils=
 literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">&gt;=3D</span></code>
operators are only defined where they make sense; for example, they raise a
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/e=
xceptions.html#TypeError" title=3D"TypeError"><code class=3D"xref py py-exc=
 docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">TypeError</span></code><=
/a> exception when one of the arguments is a complex number.</p>
<p id=3D"index-9">Non-identical instances of a class normally compare as no=
n-equal unless the
class defines the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyth=
on.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__eq__" title=3D"object.__eq__"><c=
ode class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">__eq__()</span></code></a> method.</p>
<p>Instances of a class cannot be ordered with respect to other instances o=
f the
same class, or other types of object, unless the class defines enough of th=
e
methods <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/r=
eference/datamodel.html#object.__lt__" title=3D"object.__lt__"><code class=
=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__lt_=
_()</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs=
.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__le__" title=3D"object.__le_=
_"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">__le__()</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__gt__" title=
=3D"object.__gt__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">__gt__()</span></code></a>, and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#object.__ge__" title=3D"object.__ge__"><code class=3D"xref =
py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__ge__()</span=
></code></a> (in general, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://d=
ocs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__lt__" title=3D"object.__=
lt__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">__lt__()</span></code></a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#object.__eq__" title=3D"object.__eq__"><code class=3D"xref =
py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__eq__()</span=
></code></a> are sufficient, if you want the conventional meanings of the
comparison operators).</p>
<p>The behavior of the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs=
.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#is"><code class=3D"xref std std-ke=
yword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">is</span></code></a=
> and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/ref=
erence/expressions.html#is-not"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutil=
s literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">is</span> <span class=3D"pre">no=
t</span></code></a> operators cannot be
customized; also they can be applied to any two objects and never raise an
exception.</p>
<p id=3D"index-10">Two more operations with the same syntactic priority, <a=
 class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/e=
xpressions.html#in"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal no=
translate"><span class=3D"pre">in</span></code></a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/expressions.html#not-in"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils lite=
ral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">not</span> <span class=3D"pre">in</spa=
n></code></a>, are supported by types that are <a class=3D"reference intern=
al" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-iterable"><span cl=
ass=3D"xref std std-term">iterable</span></a> or
implement the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.o=
rg/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__contains__" title=3D"object.__contai=
ns__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">__contains__()</span></code></a> method.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"numeric-types-int-float-complex">
<span id=3D"typesnumeric"></span><h2>Numeric Types =E2=80=94 <a class=3D"re=
ference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#=
int" title=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">int</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference inte=
rnal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#float" title=
=3D"float"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">float</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" =
href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#complex" title=3D"=
complex"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><spa=
n class=3D"pre">complex</span></code></a><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"ht=
tps://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#numeric-types-int-float-compl=
ex" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-11">There are three distinct numeric types: <em class=3D"dfn=
">integers</em>, <em class=3D"dfn">floating-point
numbers</em>, and <em class=3D"dfn">complex numbers</em>.  In addition, Boo=
leans are a
subtype of integers.  Integers have unlimited precision.  Floating-point
numbers are usually implemented using <span class=3D"c-expr sig sig-inline =
c"><span class=3D"kt">double</span></span> in C; information
about the precision and internal representation of floating-point
numbers for the machine on which your program is running is available
in <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/sys.html#sys.float_info" title=3D"sys.float_info"><code class=3D"xref py =
py-data docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">sys.float_info</s=
pan></code></a>.  Complex numbers have a real and imaginary
part, which are each a floating-point number.  To extract these parts
from a complex number <em>z</em>, use <code class=3D"docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">z.real</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutil=
s literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">z.imag</span></code>. (The stand=
ard
library includes the additional numeric types <a class=3D"reference interna=
l" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/fractions.html#fractions.Fract=
ion" title=3D"fractions.Fraction"><code class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils li=
teral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">fractions.Fraction</span></code></a>=
, for
rationals, and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.=
org/3/library/decimal.html#decimal.Decimal" title=3D"decimal.Decimal"><code=
 class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
decimal.Decimal</span></code></a>, for floating-point numbers with
user-definable precision.)</p>
<p id=3D"index-12">Numbers are created by numeric literals or as the result=
 of built-in functions
and operators.  Unadorned integer literals (including hex, octal and binary
numbers) yield integers.  Numeric literals containing a decimal point or an
exponent sign yield floating-point numbers.  Appending <code class=3D"docut=
ils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">'j'</span></code> or <code cla=
ss=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">'J'</span></code> t=
o a
numeric literal yields an imaginary number (a complex number with a zero re=
al
part) which you can add to an integer or float to get a complex number with=
 real
and imaginary parts.</p>
<p>The constructors <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.py=
thon.org/3/library/functions.html#int" title=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py=
 py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">int()</span></co=
de></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/=
library/functions.html#float" title=3D"float"><code class=3D"xref py py-fun=
c docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float()</span></code></=
a>, and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/f=
unctions.html#complex" title=3D"complex"><code class=3D"xref py py-func doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">complex()</span></code></a> =
can be used to produce numbers of a specific type.</p>
<p id=3D"index-13">Python fully supports mixed arithmetic: when a binary ar=
ithmetic operator has
operands of different numeric types, the operand with the =E2=80=9Cnarrower=
=E2=80=9D type is
widened to that of the other, where integer is narrower than floating point=
.
Arithmetic with complex and real operands is defined by the usual mathemati=
cal
formula, for example:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"n">x</=
