=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"o">-</span><span=
 class=3D"mf">2.0</span><span class=3D"p">)</span><span class=3D"o">.</span=
><span class=3D"n">is_integer</span><span class=3D"p">()</span>
<span class=3D"go">True</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span clas=
s=3D"mf">3.2</span><span class=3D"p">)</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><spa=
n class=3D"n">is_integer</span><span class=3D"p">()</span>
<span class=3D"go">False</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<p>Two methods support conversion to
and from hexadecimal strings.  Since Python=E2=80=99s floats are stored
internally as binary numbers, converting a float to or from a
<em>decimal</em> string usually involves a small rounding error.  In
contrast, hexadecimal strings allow exact representation and
specification of floating-point numbers.  This can be useful when
debugging, and in numerical work.</p>
<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"float.hex">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">float.</span>=
</span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">hex</span></sp=
an><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span><a c=
lass=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html=
#float.hex" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>Return a representation of a floating-point number as a hexadecimal
string.  For finite floating-point numbers, this representation
will always include a leading <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate">=
<span class=3D"pre">0x</span></code> and a trailing <code class=3D"docutils=
 literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">p</span></code> and
exponent.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"float.fromhex">
<em class=3D"property"><span class=3D"k"><span class=3D"pre">classmethod</s=
pan></span><span class=3D"w"> </span></em><span class=3D"sig-prename desccl=
assname"><span class=3D"pre">float.</span></span><span class=3D"sig-name de=
scname"><span class=3D"pre">fromhex</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">=
(</span><em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">s</sp=
an></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span><a class=3D"headerlink" hr=
ef=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#float.fromhex" title=
=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>Class method to return the float represented by a hexadecimal
string <em>s</em>.  The string <em>s</em> may have leading and trailing
whitespace.</p>
</dd></dl>

<p>Note that <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.or=
g/3/library/stdtypes.html#float.hex" title=3D"float.hex"><code class=3D"xre=
f py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float.hex()<=
/span></code></a> is an instance method, while
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#float.fromhex" title=3D"float.fromhex"><code class=3D"xref py =
py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float.fromhex()</=
span></code></a> is a class method.</p>
<p>A hexadecimal string takes the form:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"p">[</=
span><span class=3D"n">sign</span><span class=3D"p">]</span> <span class=3D=
"p">[</span><span class=3D"s1">'0x'</span><span class=3D"p">]</span> <span =
class=3D"n">integer</span> <span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"s1">'.'=
</span> <span class=3D"n">fraction</span><span class=3D"p">]</span> <span c=
lass=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"s1">'p'</span> <span class=3D"n">exponent=
</span><span class=3D"p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>where the optional <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">sign</span></code> may by either <code class=3D"docutils litera=
l notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">+</span></code> or <code class=3D"docuti=
ls literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">-</span></code>, <code class=3D=
"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">integer</span></code>
and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">fracti=
on</span></code> are strings of hexadecimal digits, and <code class=3D"docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">exponent</span></code>
is a decimal integer with an optional leading sign.  Case is not
significant, and there must be at least one hexadecimal digit in
either the integer or the fraction.  This syntax is similar to the
syntax specified in section 6.4.4.2 of the C99 standard, and also to
the syntax used in Java 1.5 onwards.  In particular, the output of
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#float.hex" title=3D"float.hex"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float.hex()</span></code>=
</a> is usable as a hexadecimal floating-point literal in
C or Java code, and hexadecimal strings produced by C=E2=80=99s <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">%a</span></code> form=
at
character or Java=E2=80=99s <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">Double.toHexString</span></code> are accepted by
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#float.fromhex" title=3D"float.fromhex"><code class=3D"xref py =
py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float.fromhex()</=
span></code></a>.</p>
<p>Note that the exponent is written in decimal rather than hexadecimal,
and that it gives the power of 2 by which to multiply the coefficient.
For example, the hexadecimal string <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">0x3.a7p10</span></code> represents the
floating-point number <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">(3</span> <span class=3D"pre">+</span> <span class=3D"pre">10./=
16</span> <span class=3D"pre">+</span> <span class=3D"pre">7./16**2)</span>=
 <span class=3D"pre">*</span> <span class=3D"pre">2.0**10</span></code>, or
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">3740.0</sp=
an></code>:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">float</span><span class=3D"o">.</span>=
<span class=3D"n">fromhex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"s1=
">'0x3.a7p10'</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">3740.0</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>Applying the reverse conversion to <code class=3D"docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">3740.0</span></code> gives a different
hexadecimal string representing the same number:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">float</span><span class=3D"o">.</span>=
<span class=3D"n">hex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"mf">37=
40.0</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">'0x1.d380000000000p+11'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"additional-methods-on-complex">
