pan class=3D"pre">tuple</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" =
href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#range" title=3D"ran=
ge"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span cla=
ss=3D"pre">range</span></code></a><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://d=
ocs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#sequence-types-list-tuple-range" tit=
le=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p>There are three basic sequence types: lists, tuples, and range objects.
Additional sequence types tailored for processing of
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#binaryseq"><span class=3D"std std-ref">binary data</span></a> =
and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libra=
ry/stdtypes.html#textseq"><span class=3D"std std-ref">text strings</span></=
a> are
described in dedicated sections.</p>
<section id=3D"common-sequence-operations">
<span id=3D"typesseq-common"></span><h3>Common Sequence Operations<a class=
=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#com=
mon-sequence-operations" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-19">The operations in the following table are supported by m=
ost sequence types,
both mutable and immutable. The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"htt=
