translate"><span class=3D"pre">len(s)</span></code> if they are greater.
When <em>k</em> is negative, <em>i</em> and <em>j</em> are reduced to <code=
 class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">len(s)</span> <=
span class=3D"pre">-</span> <span class=3D"pre">1</span></code> if
they are greater.  If <em>i</em> or <em>j</em> are omitted or <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span></code>, t=
hey become
=E2=80=9Cend=E2=80=9D values (which end depends on the sign of <em>k</em>).=
  Note, <em>k</em> cannot be zero.
If <em>k</em> is <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">None</span></code>, it is treated like <code class=3D"docutils lit=
eral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">1</span></code>.</p></li>
<li><p>Concatenating immutable sequences always results in a new object.  T=
his
means that building up a sequence by repeated concatenation will have a
quadratic runtime cost in the total sequence length.  To get a linear
runtime cost, you must switch to one of the alternatives below:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>if concatenating <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://doc=
s.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref=
 py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str</span></=
code></a> objects, you can build a list and use
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#str.join" title=3D"str.join"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth do=
cutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str.join()</span></code></a=
> at the end or else write to an <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"ht=
tps://docs.python.org/3/library/io.html#io.StringIO" title=3D"io.StringIO">=
<code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">io.StringIO</span></code></a>
instance and retrieve its value when complete</p></li>
<li><p>if concatenating <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://doc=
s.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"=
xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</s=
pan></code></a> objects, you can similarly use
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#bytes.join" title=3D"bytes.join"><code class=3D"xref py py-met=
h docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes.join()</span></co=
de></a> or <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/library/io.html#io.BytesIO" title=3D"io.BytesIO"><code class=3D"xref py p=
y-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">io.BytesIO</span>=
</code></a>, or you can do in-place
concatenation with a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.p=
ython.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytearray" title=3D"bytearray"><code clas=
s=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">byt=
earray</span></code></a> object.  <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"h=
ttps://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytearray" title=3D"bytearra=
y"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">bytearray</span></code></a>
objects are mutable and have an efficient overallocation mechanism</p></li>
<li><p>if concatenating <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://doc=
s.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#tuple" title=3D"tuple"><code class=3D"=
xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">tuple</s=
pan></code></a> objects, extend a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"h=
ttps://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#list" title=3D"list"><code c=
lass=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
list</span></code></a> instead</p></li>
