<section id=3D"text-sequence-type-str">
<span id=3D"textseq"></span><h2>Text Sequence Type =E2=80=94 <a class=3D"re=
ference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#s=
tr" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">str</span></code></a><a class=3D"headerlink" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#text-sequence-type-str"=
 title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p>Textual data in Python is handled with <a class=3D"reference internal" h=
ref=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><=
code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D=
"pre">str</span></code></a> objects, or <em class=3D"dfn">strings</em>.
Strings are immutable
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#typesseq"><span class=3D"std std-ref">sequences</span></a> of =
Unicode code points.  String literals are
written in a variety of ways:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>Single quotes: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">'allows</span> <span class=3D"pre">embedded</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">"double"</span> <span class=3D"pre">quotes'</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Double quotes: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">"allows</span> <span class=3D"pre">embedded</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">'single'</span> <span class=3D"pre">quotes"</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Triple quoted: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">'''Three</span> <span class=3D"pre">single</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">quotes'''</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">"""Three</span> <span class=3D"pre">double</span> <=
span class=3D"pre">quotes"""</span></code></p></li>
</ul>
<p>Triple quoted strings may span multiple lines - all associated whitespac=
e will
be included in the string literal.</p>
<p>String literals that are part of a single expression and have only white=
space
between them will be implicitly converted to a single string literal. That
is, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">("spam=
</span> <span class=3D"pre">"</span> <span class=3D"pre">"eggs")</span> <sp=
an class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">"spam</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">eggs"</span></code>.</p>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/lexical_analysis.html#strings"><span class=3D"std std-ref">String a=
nd Bytes literals</span></a> for more about the various forms of string lit=
eral,
including supported <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.py=
thon.org/3/reference/lexical_analysis.html#escape-sequences"><span class=3D=
"std std-ref">escape sequences</span></a>, and the <code class=3D"docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">r</span></code> (=E2=80=9Craw=E2=
=80=9D) prefix that
disables most escape sequence processing.</p>
<p>Strings may also be created from other objects using the <a class=3D"ref=
erence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#st=
r" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">str</span></code></a>
constructor.</p>
<p>Since there is no separate =E2=80=9Ccharacter=E2=80=9D type, indexing a =
string produces
strings of length 1. That is, for a non-empty string <em>s</em>, <code clas=
s=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">s[0]</span> <span cl=
ass=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">s[0:1]</span></code>.</p>
<p id=3D"index-29">There is also no mutable string type, but <a class=3D"re=
ference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#s=
tr.join" title=3D"str.join"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal=
 notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str.join()</span></code></a> or
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/i=
o.html#io.StringIO" title=3D"io.StringIO"><code class=3D"xref py py-class d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">io.StringIO</span></code><=
/a> can be used to efficiently construct strings from
multiple fragments.</p>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.3: </span>F=
or backwards compatibility with the Python 2 series, the <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">u</span></code> prefix is
once again permitted on string literals. It has no effect on the meaning
of string literals and cannot be combined with the <code class=3D"docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">r</span></code> prefix.</p>
</div>
