<section id=3D"binary-sequence-types-bytes-bytearray-memoryview">
<span id=3D"binaryseq"></span><span id=3D"index-40"></span><h2>Binary Seque=
nce Types =E2=80=94 <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.py=
thon.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref=
 py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span>=
</code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.or=
g/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytearray" title=3D"bytearray"><code class=3D"xre=
f py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytearray</=
span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyth=
on.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#memoryview" title=3D"memoryview"><code class=
=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">memo=
ryview</span></code></a><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python=
.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#binary-sequence-types-bytes-bytearray-memoryvi=
ew" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-41">The core built-in types for manipulating binary data are=
 <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/=
stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docuti=
ls literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span></code></a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#bytearray" title=3D"bytearray"><code class=3D"xref py py-class=
 docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytearray</span></code><=
/a>. They are supported by <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://=
docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#memoryview" title=3D"memoryview"><c=
ode class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"=
pre">memoryview</span></code></a> which uses
the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/c-api=
/buffer.html#bufferobjects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">buffer protocol</sp=
an></a> to access the memory of other
binary objects without needing to make a copy.</p>
<p>The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/li=
brary/array.html#module-array" title=3D"array: Space efficient arrays of un=
iformly typed numeric values."><code class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils liter=
al notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">array</span></code></a> module supports=
 efficient storage of basic data types like
32-bit integers and IEEE754 double-precision floating values.</p>
<section id=3D"bytes-objects">
<span id=3D"typebytes"></span><h3>Bytes Objects<a class=3D"headerlink" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes-objects" title=3D=
"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-42">Bytes objects are immutable sequences of single bytes. S=
ince many major
binary protocols are based on the ASCII text encoding, bytes objects offer
several methods that are only valid when working with ASCII compatible
data and are closely related to string objects in a variety of other ways.<=
/p>
<dl class=3D"py class">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"bytes">
<em class=3D"property"><span class=3D"k"><span class=3D"pre">class</span></=
span><span class=3D"w"> </span></em><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span=
 class=3D"pre">bytes</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em cla=
ss=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">source</span></span>=
<span class=3D"o"><span class=3D"pre">=3D</span></span><span class=3D"defau=
lt_value"><span class=3D"pre">b''</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-pare=
n">)</span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py">
<em class=3D"property"><span class=3D"k"><span class=3D"pre">class</span></=
span><span class=3D"w"> </span></em><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span=
 class=3D"pre">bytes</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em cla=
ss=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">source</span></span>=
</em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">encodi=
ng</span></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">errors</span></span><span class=3D"o"><span class=3D"pre">=3D</sp=
an></span><span class=3D"default_value"><span class=3D"pre">'strict'</span>=
</span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span></dt>
<dd><p>Firstly, the syntax for bytes literals is largely the same as that f=
or string
literals, except that a <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">b</span></code> prefix is added:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>Single quotes: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">b'still</span> <span class=3D"pre">allows</span> <span class=3D=
"pre">embedded</span> <span class=3D"pre">"double"</span> <span class=3D"pr=
e">quotes'</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Double quotes: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">b"still</span> <span class=3D"pre">allows</span> <span class=3D=
"pre">embedded</span> <span class=3D"pre">'single'</span> <span class=3D"pr=
e">quotes"</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Triple quoted: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">b'''3</span> <span class=3D"pre">single</span> <span class=3D"p=
re">quotes'''</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">b"""3</span> <span class=3D"pre">double</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"pre">quotes"""</span></code></p></li>
</ul>
<p>Only ASCII characters are permitted in bytes literals (regardless of the
declared source code encoding). Any binary values over 127 must be entered
into bytes literals using the appropriate escape sequence.</p>
<p>As with string literals, bytes literals may also use a <code class=3D"do=
cutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">r</span></code> prefix to d=
isable
processing of escape sequences. See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/lexical_analysis.html#strings"><span c=
lass=3D"std std-ref">String and Bytes literals</span></a> for more about th=
e various
forms of bytes literal, including supported escape sequences.</p>
<p>While bytes literals and representations are based on ASCII text, bytes
objects actually behave like immutable sequences of integers, with each
value in the sequence restricted such that <code class=3D"docutils literal =
notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">0</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;=3D</span=
> <span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">256</span></code> (attempts to
violate this restriction will trigger <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#ValueError" title=3D"=
ValueError"><code class=3D"xref py py-exc docutils literal notranslate"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">ValueError</span></code></a>). This is done
deliberately to emphasise that while many binary formats include ASCII base=
d
elements and can be usefully manipulated with some text-oriented algorithms=
,
this is not generally the case for arbitrary binary data (blindly applying
text processing algorithms to binary data formats that are not ASCII
compatible will usually lead to data corruption).</p>
<p>In addition to the literal forms, bytes objects can be created in a numb=
er of
other ways:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>A zero-filled bytes object of a specified length: <code class=3D"doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes(10)</span></code></p><=
/li>
<li><p>From an iterable of integers: <code class=3D"docutils literal notran=
slate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes(range(20))</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Copying existing binary data via the buffer protocol:  <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes(obj)</span></co=
de></p></li>
</ul>
<p>Also see the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python=
.org/3/library/functions.html#func-bytes"><span class=3D"std std-ref">bytes=
</span></a> built-in.</p>
<p>Since 2 hexadecimal digits correspond precisely to a single byte, hexade=
cimal
numbers are a commonly used format for describing binary data. Accordingly,
the bytes type has an additional class method to read data in that format:<=
/p>
<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"bytes.fromhex">
<em class=3D"property"><span class=3D"k"><span class=3D"pre">classmethod</s=
pan></span><span class=3D"w"> </span></em><span class=3D"sig-name descname"=
><span class=3D"pre">fromhex</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span=
><em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">string</span=
></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"positional-only-separ=
ator o"><abbr title=3D"Positional-only parameter separator (PEP 570)"><span=
 class=3D"pre">/</span></abbr></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span=
><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes=
.html#bytes.fromhex" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>This <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org=
/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref py py-c=
lass docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span></code><=
/a> class method returns a bytes object, decoding the
given string object.  The string must contain two hexadecimal digits per
byte, with ASCII whitespace being ignored.</p>
<div class=3D"doctest highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highligh=
t" style=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"butto=
n" title=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=
=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">bytes</span><span class=3D"o=
">.</span><span class=3D"n">fromhex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span c=
lass=3D"s1">'2Ef0 F1f2  '</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">b'.\xf0\xf1\xf2'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.7: </span><=
a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/st=
dtypes.html#bytes.fromhex" title=3D"bytes.fromhex"><code class=3D"xref py p=
y-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes.fromhex()</s=
pan></code></a> now skips all ASCII whitespace in the string,
not just spaces.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.14: </span>=
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#bytes.fromhex" title=3D"bytes.fromhex"><code class=3D"xref py =
py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes.fromhex()</=
span></code></a> now accepts ASCII <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"=
https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><cod=
e class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">bytes</span></code></a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.=
html#term-bytes-like-object"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">bytes-like o=
bjects</span></a> as input.</p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<p>A reverse conversion function exists to transform a bytes object into it=
s
hexadecimal representation.</p>
<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"bytes.hex">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">hex</span></span><spa=
n class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"keywor=
d-only-separator o"><abbr title=3D"Keyword-only parameters separator (PEP 3=
102)"><span class=3D"pre">*</span></abbr></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-par=
am"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">bytes_per_sep</span></span><span =
class=3D"o"><span class=3D"pre">=3D</span></span><span class=3D"default_val=
ue"><span class=3D"pre">1</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</sp=
an><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtyp=
es.html#bytes.hex" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">hex</span></span><spa=
n class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">sep</span></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span clas=
s=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">bytes_per_sep</span></span><span class=3D"o"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">=3D</span></span><span class=3D"default_value"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">1</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span></dt>
<dd><p>Return a string object containing two hexadecimal digits for each
byte in the instance.</p>
<div class=3D"doctest highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highligh=
t" style=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"butto=
n" title=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=
=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"sa">b</span><span class=3D"s1">'=
</span><span class=3D"se">\xf0\xf1\xf2</span><span class=3D"s1">'</span><sp=
an class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">hex</span><span class=3D"p">()</sp=
an>
<span class=3D"go">'f0f1f2'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>If you want to make the hex string easier to read, you can specify a
single character separator <em>sep</em> parameter to include in the output.
By default, this separator will be included between each byte.
A second optional <em>bytes_per_sep</em> parameter controls the spacing.
Positive values calculate the separator position from the right,
negative values from the left.</p>
<div class=3D"doctest highlight-default notranslate"><div class=3D"highligh=
t" style=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"butto=
n" title=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=
=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">value</span> <span class=3D"o=
">=3D</span> <span class=3D"sa">b</span><span class=3D"s1">'</span><span cl=
ass=3D"se">\xf0\xf1\xf2</span><span class=3D"s1">'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">value</span><span =
class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">hex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"s1">'-'</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">'f0-f1-f2'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">value</span><span =
class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">hex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"s1">'_'</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"mi">2=
</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">'f0_f1f2'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"sa">b</span><span cla=
ss=3D"s1">'UUDDLRLRAB'</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">he=
x</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"s1">' '</span><span class=
=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"o">-</span><span class=3D"mi">4</span><span =
class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">'55554444 4c524c52 4142'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified added">Added in version 3.5.</span></p>
</div>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.8: </span><=
a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/st=
dtypes.html#bytes.hex" title=3D"bytes.hex"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes.hex()</span></code><=
/a> now supports optional <em>sep</em> and <em>bytes_per_sep</em>
parameters to insert separators between bytes in the hex output.</p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

</dd></dl>

<p>Since bytes objects are sequences of integers (akin to a tuple), for a b=
ytes
object <em>b</em>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">b[0]</span></code> will be an integer, while <code class=3D"docuti=
ls literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">b[0:1]</span></code> will be a =
bytes
object of length 1.  (This contrasts with text strings, where both indexing
and slicing will produce a string of length 1)</p>
<p>The representation of bytes objects uses the literal format (<code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">b'...'</span></code>)
since it is often more useful than e.g. <code class=3D"docutils literal not=
ranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes([46,</span> <span class=3D"pre">46,</sp=
an> <span class=3D"pre">46])</span></code>.  You can
always convert a bytes object into a list of integers using <code class=3D"=
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">list(b)</span></code>.</p=
>
</section>
<section id=3D"bytearray-objects">
<span id=3D"typebytearray"></span><h3>Bytearray Objects<a class=3D"headerli=
nk" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytearray-objec=
ts" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-43"><a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyt=
hon.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytearray" title=3D"bytearray"><code class=
