s=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">mapping</span></span>=
</em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"positional-only-separator o">=
<abbr title=3D"Positional-only parameter separator (PEP 570)"><span class=
=3D"pre">/</span></abbr></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=
=3D"o"><span class=3D"pre">**</span></span><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D=
"pre">kwargs</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span></dt>
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py">
<em class=3D"property"><span class=3D"k"><span class=3D"pre">class</span></=
span><span class=3D"w"> </span></em><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span=
 class=3D"pre">dict</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em clas=
s=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">iterable</span></span=
></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"positional-only-separator o"=
><abbr title=3D"Positional-only parameter separator (PEP 570)"><span class=
=3D"pre">/</span></abbr></span></em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=
=3D"o"><span class=3D"pre">**</span></span><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D=
"pre">kwargs</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span></dt>
<dd><p>Return a new dictionary initialized from an optional positional argu=
ment
and a possibly empty set of keyword arguments.</p>
<p>Dictionaries can be created by several means:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>Use a comma-separated list of <code class=3D"docutils literal notran=
slate"><span class=3D"pre">key:</span> <span class=3D"pre">value</span></co=
de> pairs within braces:
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">{'jack':</=
span> <span class=3D"pre">4098,</span> <span class=3D"pre">'sjoerd':</span>=
 <span class=3D"pre">4127}</span></code> or <code class=3D"docutils literal=
 notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">{4098:</span> <span class=3D"pre">'jack',=
</span> <span class=3D"pre">4127:</span> <span class=3D"pre">'sjoerd'}</spa=
n></code></p></li>
<li><p>Use a dict comprehension: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">{}</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal no=
translate"><span class=3D"pre">{x:</span> <span class=3D"pre">x</span> <spa=
n class=3D"pre">**</span> <span class=3D"pre">2</span> <span class=3D"pre">=
for</span> <span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=3D"pre">in</span> <span=
 class=3D"pre">range(10)}</span></code></p></li>
<li><p>Use the type constructor: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">dict()</span></code>,
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict([('fo=
o',</span> <span class=3D"pre">100),</span> <span class=3D"pre">('bar',</sp=
an> <span class=3D"pre">200)])</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils liter=
al notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict(foo=3D100,</span> <span class=3D"p=
re">bar=3D200)</span></code></p></li>
</ul>
<p>If no positional argument is given, an empty dictionary is created.
If a positional argument is given and it defines a <code class=3D"docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">keys()</span></code> method, a
dictionary is created by calling <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"ht=
tps://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__getitem__" title=
=3D"object.__getitem__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal not=
ranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__getitem__()</span></code></a> on the argume=
nt with
each returned key from the method.  Otherwise, the positional argument must=
 be an
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.=
html#term-iterable"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">iterable</span></a> o=
bject.  Each item in the iterable must itself be an iterable
with exactly two elements.  The first element of each item becomes a key in=
 the
new dictionary, and the second element the corresponding value.  If a key o=
ccurs
more than once, the last value for that key becomes the corresponding value=
 in
the new dictionary.</p>
<p>If keyword arguments are given, the keyword arguments and their values a=
re
added to the dictionary created from the positional argument.  If a key
being added is already present, the value from the keyword argument
replaces the value from the positional argument.</p>
<p>Dictionaries compare equal if and only if they have the same <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">(key,</span>
<span class=3D"pre">value)</span></code> pairs (regardless of ordering). Or=
der comparisons (=E2=80=98&lt;=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98&lt;=3D=E2=80=99, =E2=80=
=98&gt;=3D=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98&gt;=E2=80=99) raise
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/e=
xceptions.html#TypeError" title=3D"TypeError"><code class=3D"xref py py-exc=
 docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">TypeError</span></code><=
/a>.  To illustrate dictionary creation and equality,
the following examples all return a dictionary equal to
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">{"one":</s=
pan> <span class=3D"pre">1,</span> <span class=3D"pre">"two":</span> <span =
class=3D"pre">2,</span> <span class=3D"pre">"three":</span> <span class=3D"=
pre">3}</span></code>:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
