<div class=3D"admonition seealso">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">See also</p>
<p><a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/types.html#types.MappingProxyType" title=3D"types.MappingProxyType"><code=
 class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">types.MappingProxyType</span></code></a> can be used to create a read-onl=
y view
of a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libr=
ary/stdtypes.html#dict" title=3D"dict"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict</span></code></a>.</p>
</div>
<section id=3D"dictionary-view-objects">
<span id=3D"dict-views"></span><h3>Dictionary view objects<a class=3D"heade=
rlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#dictionary-v=
iew-objects" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>The objects returned by <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://=
docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#dict.keys" title=3D"dict.keys"><cod=
e class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">dict.keys()</span></code></a>, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"ht=
tps://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#dict.values" title=3D"dict.va=
lues"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">dict.values()</span></code></a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#dict.items" title=3D"dict.items"><code class=3D"xref py py-met=
h docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict.items()</span></co=
de></a> are <em>view objects</em>.  They provide a dynamic view on the
dictionary=E2=80=99s entries, which means that when the dictionary changes,=
 the view
reflects these changes.</p>
<p>Dictionary views can be iterated over to yield their respective data, an=
d
support membership tests:</p>
<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">len(dictview)</span><=
/span></dt>
<dd><p>Return the number of entries in the dictionary.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">iter(dictview)</span>=
</span></dt>
<dd><p>Return an iterator over the keys, values or items (represented as tu=
ples of
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">(key,</spa=
n> <span class=3D"pre">value)</span></code>) in the dictionary.</p>
<p>Keys and values are iterated over in insertion order.
This allows the creation of <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">(value,</span> <span class=3D"pre">key)</span></code> pai=
rs
using <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/lib=
rary/functions.html#zip" title=3D"zip"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docut=
ils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">zip()</span></code></a>: <code=
 class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">pairs</span> <s=
pan class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">zip(d.values(),</span> <sp=
an class=3D"pre">d.keys())</span></code>.  Another way to
create the same list is <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">pairs</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pr=
e">[(v,</span> <span class=3D"pre">k)</span> <span class=3D"pre">for</span>=
 <span class=3D"pre">(k,</span> <span class=3D"pre">v)</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">in</span> <span class=3D"pre">d.items()]</span></code>.</p>
<p>Iterating views while adding or deleting entries in the dictionary may r=
aise
a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library=
/exceptions.html#RuntimeError" title=3D"RuntimeError"><code class=3D"xref p=
y py-exc docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">RuntimeError</sp=
an></code></a> or fail to iterate over all entries.</p>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.7: </span>D=
ictionary order is guaranteed to be insertion order.</p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">x</span> <span class=
=3D"pre">in</span> <span class=3D"pre">dictview</span></span></dt>
<dd><p>Return <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">True</span></code> if <em>x</em> is in the underlying dictionary=E2=80=
=99s keys, values or
items (in the latter case, <em>x</em> should be a <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">(key,</span> <span class=3D"pre">va=
lue)</span></code> tuple).</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">reversed(dictview)</s=
pan></span></dt>
<dd><p>Return a reverse iterator over the keys, values or items of the dict=
ionary.
The view will be iterated in reverse order of the insertion.</p>
<div class=3D"versionchanged">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified changed">Changed in version 3.8: </span>D=
ictionary views are now reversible.</p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">dictview.mapping</spa=
n></span></dt>
<dd><p>Return a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python=
.org/3/library/types.html#types.MappingProxyType" title=3D"types.MappingPro=
xyType"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span=
 class=3D"pre">types.MappingProxyType</span></code></a> that wraps the orig=
inal
dictionary to which the view refers.</p>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified added">Added in version 3.10.</span></p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<p>Keys views are set-like since their entries are unique and <a class=3D"r=
eference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-has=
hable"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">hashable</span></a>.
Items views also have set-like operations since the (key, value) pairs
are unique and the keys are hashable.
If all values in an items view are hashable as well,
then the items view can interoperate with other sets.
(Values views are not treated as set-like
since the entries are generally not unique.)  For set-like views, all of th=
e
operations defined for the abstract base class <a class=3D"reference intern=
al" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/collections.abc.html#collecti=
ons.abc.Set" title=3D"collections.abc.Set"><code class=3D"xref py py-class =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">collections.abc.Set</span=
></code></a> are
available (for example, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">=3D=3D</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span></code>, or <code class=3D"docutils li=
teral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">^</span></code>).  While using set o=
perators,
set-like views accept any iterable as the other operand,
unlike sets which only accept sets as the input.</p>
<p>An example of dictionary view usage:</p>
