<section id=3D"context-manager-types">
<span id=3D"typecontextmanager"></span><h2>Context Manager Types<a class=3D=
"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#contex=
t-manager-types" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-55">Python=E2=80=99s <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#with"><code class=
=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
with</span></code></a> statement supports the concept of a runtime context
defined by a context manager.  This is implemented using a pair of methods
that allow user-defined classes to define a runtime context that is entered
before the statement body is executed and exited when the statement ends:</=
p>
<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"contextmanager.__enter__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">contextmanage=
r.</span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__ent=
er__</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><span class=3D"sig-pare=
n">)</span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/stdtypes.html#contextmanager.__enter__" title=3D"Link to this definition"=
>=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>Enter the runtime context and return either this object or another o=
bject
related to the runtime context. The value returned by this method is bound =
to
the identifier in the <code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal =
notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">as</span></code> clause of <a class=3D"ref=
erence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts=
.html#with"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code></a> statements using
this context manager.</p>
<p>An example of a context manager that returns itself is a <a class=3D"ref=
erence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-file-=
object"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">file object</span></a>.
File objects return themselves from __enter__() to allow <a class=3D"refere=
nce internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#open=
" title=3D"open"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslat=
e"><span class=3D"pre">open()</span></code></a> to be
used as the context expression in a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#with"><code class=
=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
with</span></code></a> statement.</p>
<p>An example of a context manager that returns a related object is the one
returned by <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org=
/3/library/decimal.html#decimal.localcontext" title=3D"decimal.localcontext=
"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">decimal.localcontext()</span></code></a>. These managers set the a=
ctive
decimal context to a copy of the original decimal context and then return t=
he
copy. This allows changes to be made to the current decimal context in the =
body
of the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/compound_stmts.html#with"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docut=
ils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code></a> stateme=
nt without affecting code outside the
<code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><span cla=
ss=3D"pre">with</span></code> statement.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py method">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"contextmanager.__exit__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">contextmanage=
r.</span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__exi=
t__</span></span><span class=3D"sig-paren">(</span><em class=3D"sig-param">=
<span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">exc_type</span></span></em>, <em clas=
s=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">exc_val</span></span>=
</em>, <em class=3D"sig-param"><span class=3D"n"><span class=3D"pre">exc_tb=
</span></span></em><span class=3D"sig-paren">)</span><a class=3D"headerlink=
" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#contextmanager.__=
exit__" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>Exit the runtime context and return a Boolean flag indicating if any=
 exception
that occurred should be suppressed. If an exception occurred while executin=
g the
body of the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org=
/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#with"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code></a> st=
atement, the arguments contain the exception type,
value and traceback information. Otherwise, all three arguments are <code c=
lass=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span></code=
>.</p>
<p>Returning a true value from this method will cause the <a class=3D"refer=
ence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.h=
tml#with"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"=
><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code></a> statement
to suppress the exception and continue execution with the statement immedia=
tely
following the <code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code> statement. Otherwise the except=
ion continues
propagating after this method has finished executing.</p>
<p>If this method raises an exception while handling an earlier exception f=
rom the
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/compound_stmts.html#with"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils lit=
eral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">with</span></code></a> block, the new=
 exception is raised, and the original exception
is stored in its <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pytho=
n.org/3/library/exceptions.html#BaseException.__context__" title=3D"BaseExc=
eption.__context__"><code class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">__context__</span></code></a> attribute.</p>
<p>The exception passed in should never be reraised explicitly - instead, t=
his
method should return a false value to indicate that the method completed
successfully and does not want to suppress the raised exception. This allow=
s
context management code to easily detect whether or not an <a class=3D"refe=
rence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#=
object.__exit__" title=3D"object.__exit__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__exit__()</span></code></=
a>
method has actually failed.</p>
</dd></dl>

<p>Python defines several context managers to support easy thread synchroni=
sation,
prompt closure of files or other objects, and simpler manipulation of the a=
ctive
decimal arithmetic context. The specific types are not treated specially be=
yond
their implementation of the context management protocol. See the
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/c=
ontextlib.html#module-contextlib" title=3D"contextlib: Utilities for with-s=
tatement contexts."><code class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">contextlib</span></code></a> module for some examp=
les.</p>
<p>Python=E2=80=99s <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.py=
thon.org/3/glossary.html#term-generator"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">=
generator</span></a>s and the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https=
://docs.python.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.contextmanager" tit=
le=3D"contextlib.contextmanager"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">contextlib.contextmanager</span></c=
ode></a> decorator
provide a convenient way to implement these protocols.  If a generator func=
tion is
decorated with the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyt=
hon.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.contextmanager" title=3D"conte=
xtlib.contextmanager"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notr=
anslate"><span class=3D"pre">contextlib.contextmanager</span></code></a> de=
corator, it will return a
context manager implementing the necessary <a class=3D"reference internal" =
href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#contextmanager.__en=
ter__" title=3D"contextmanager.__enter__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth do=
cutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__enter__()</span></code></=
a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#contextmanager.__exit__" title=3D"contextmanager.__exit__"><co=
de class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">__exit__()</span></code></a> methods, rather than the iterator produced =
by an
undecorated generator function.</p>
<p>Note that there is no specific slot for any of these methods in the type
structure for Python objects in the Python/C API. Extension types wanting t=
o
define these methods must provide them as a normal Python accessible method=
.
Compared to the overhead of setting up the runtime context, the overhead of=
 a
single class dictionary lookup is negligible.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"type-annotation-types-generic-alias-union">
<h2>Type Annotation Types =E2=80=94 <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#types-genericalias"><span =
class=3D"std std-ref">Generic Alias</span></a>, <a class=3D"reference inter=
nal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#types-union"><=
span class=3D"std std-ref">Union</span></a><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"=
https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#type-annotation-types-gener=
ic-alias-union" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p id=3D"index-56">The core built-in types for <a class=3D"reference intern=
al" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-annotation"><span =
class=3D"xref std std-term">type annotations</span></a> are
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#types-genericalias"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Generic Alias<=
/span></a> and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.=
org/3/library/stdtypes.html#types-union"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Union<=
/span></a>.</p>
<section id=3D"generic-alias-type">
<span id=3D"types-genericalias"></span><h3>Generic Alias Type<a class=3D"he=
aderlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#generic-a=
lias-type" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-57"><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></code> objects are generally created by
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/expressions.html#subscriptions"><span class=3D"std std-ref">subscripting</=
span></a> a class. They are most often used with
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#sequence-types"><span class=3D"std std-ref">container class=
es</span></a>, such as <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs=
.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#list" title=3D"list"><code class=3D"xre=
f py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">list</span>=
</code></a> or
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#dict" title=3D"dict"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict</span></code></a>. For exampl=
e, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">list[in=
t]</span></code> is a <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></code> object created
by subscripting the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">list</span></code> class with the argument <a class=3D"reference =
internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#int" tit=
le=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">int</span></code></a>.
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">GenericAli=
as</span></code> objects are intended primarily for use with
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.=
html#term-annotation"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">type annotations</s=
pan></a>.</p>
<div class=3D"admonition note">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">Note</p>
<p>It is generally only possible to subscript a class if the class implemen=
ts
the special method <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyt=
hon.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__class_getitem__" title=3D"objec=
t.__class_getitem__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notran=
slate"><span class=3D"pre">__class_getitem__()</span></code></a>.</p>
</div>
<p>A <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Gener=
icAlias</span></code> object acts as a proxy for a <a class=3D"reference in=
ternal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-generic-type">=
<span class=3D"xref std std-term">generic type</span></a>,
implementing <em>parameterized generics</em>.</p>
<p>For a container class, the
argument(s) supplied to a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://d=
ocs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#subscriptions"><span class=3D"s=
td std-ref">subscription</span></a> of the class may
indicate the type(s) of the elements an object contains. For example,
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">set[bytes]=
</span></code> can be used in type annotations to signify a <a class=3D"ref=
erence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#se=
t" title=3D"set"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">set</span></code></a> in
which all the elements are of type <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"=
https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><cod=
e class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">bytes</span></code></a>.</p>
<p>For a class which defines <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https:=
//docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__class_getitem__" titl=
e=3D"object.__class_getitem__"><code class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils lite=
ral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__class_getitem__()</span></code></a> =
but is not a
container, the argument(s) supplied to a subscription of the class will oft=
en
indicate the return type(s) of one or more methods defined on an object. Fo=
r
example, <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/=
library/re.html#module-re" title=3D"re: Regular expression operations."><co=
de class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">regular</span> <span class=3D"pre">expressions</span></code></a> can be u=
sed on both the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python=
.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-c=
lass docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str</span></code></a=
> data
type and the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.or=
g/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref py py-=
class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span></code>=
</a> data type:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>If <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
x</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">re.search('foo'=
,</span> <span class=3D"pre">'foo')</span></code>, <code class=3D"docutils =
literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">x</span></code> will be a
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/r=
e.html#match-objects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">re.Match</span></a> objec=
t where the return values of
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">x.group(0)=
</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">x[0]</span></code> will both be of type <a class=3D"reference inte=
rnal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D=
"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span c=
lass=3D"pre">str</span></code></a>. We can
represent this kind of object in type annotations with the <code class=3D"d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></code>
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">re.Match[s=
tr]</span></code>.</p></li>
<li><p>If <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
y</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">re.search(b'bar=
',</span> <span class=3D"pre">b'bar')</span></code>, (note the <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">b</span></code> for <=
a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/st=
dtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils=
 literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span></code></a>),
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">y</span></=
code> will also be an instance of <code class=3D"docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">re.Match</span></code>, but the return
values of <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
y.group(0)</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">y[0]</span></code> will both be of type
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
tdtypes.html#bytes" title=3D"bytes"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutil=
s literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">bytes</span></code></a>. In type=
 annotations, we would represent this
variety of <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/library/re.html#match-objects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">re.Match</span=
></a> objects with <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">re.Match[bytes]</span></code>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Generic=
Alias</span></code> objects are instances of the class
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/t=
ypes.html#types.GenericAlias" title=3D"types.GenericAlias"><code class=3D"x=
ref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">types.Gen=
ericAlias</span></code></a>, which can also be used to create <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></=
code>
objects directly.</p>
<dl class=3D"describe">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object">
<span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">T[X,</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"pre">Y,</span> <span class=3D"pre">...]</span></span></dt>
<dd><p>Creates a <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></code> representing a type <code class=3D"docu=
tils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">T</span></code> parameterized=
 by types
<em>X</em>, <em>Y</em>, and more depending on the <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">T</span></code> used.
For example, a function expecting a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#list" title=3D"list"><code=
 class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre=
">list</span></code></a> containing
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/f=
unctions.html#float" title=3D"float"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docuti=
ls literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">float</span></code></a> element=
s:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"k">def=
</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"nf">average</span><span cla=
ss=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">values</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> =
<span class=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">=
float</span><span class=3D"p">])</span> <span class=3D"o">-&gt;</span> <spa=
n class=3D"nb">float</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"nb">sum</span><span clas=
s=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">values</span><span class=3D"p">)</span> <=
span class=3D"o">/</span> <span class=3D"nb">len</span><span class=3D"p">(<=
/span><span class=3D"n">values</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>Another example for <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs=
.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-mapping"><span class=3D"xref std std-term"=
>mapping</span></a> objects, using a <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#dict" title=3D"dict"><c=
ode class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"=
pre">dict</span></code></a>, which
is a generic type expecting two type parameters representing the key type
and the value type.  In this example, the function expects a <code class=3D=
"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dict</span></code> with
keys of type <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.or=
g/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-clas=
s docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str</span></code></a> a=
nd values of type <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.pyth=
on.org/3/library/functions.html#int" title=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py p=
y-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">int</span></code>=
</a>:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"k">def=
</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"nf">send_post_request</span=
><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">url</span><span class=3D"p">:<=
/span> <span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=
=3D"n">body</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> <span class=3D"nb">dict</span>=
<span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">,<=
/span> <span class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">])</span> <span class=
=3D"o">-&gt;</span> <span class=3D"kc">None</span><span class=3D"p">:</span=
>
    <span class=3D"o">...</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<p>The builtin functions <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://do=
cs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#isinstance" title=3D"isinstance"><co=
de class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">isinstance()</span></code></a> and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#issubclass" title=3D"i=
ssubclass"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">issubclass()</span></code></a> do not accept
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">GenericAli=
as</span></code> types for their second argument:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">isinstance</span><span class=3D"p">([<=
/span><span class=3D"mi">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"=
mi">2</span><span class=3D"p">],</span> <span class=3D"nb">list</span><span=
 class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">])</spa=
n>
<span class=3D"gt">Traceback (most recent call last):</span>
  File <span class=3D"nb">"&lt;stdin&gt;"</span>, line <span class=3D"m">1<=
/span>, in <span class=3D"n">&lt;module&gt;</span>
<span class=3D"gr">TypeError</span>: <span class=3D"n">isinstance() argumen=
t 2 cannot be a parameterized generic</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>The Python runtime does not enforce <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-annotation"><span class=3D=
"xref std std-term">type annotations</span></a>.
This extends to generic types and their type parameters. When creating
a container object from a <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><spa=
n class=3D"pre">GenericAlias</span></code>, the elements in the container a=
re not checked
against their type. For example, the following code is discouraged, but wil=
l
run without errors:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">t</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <=
span class=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">s=
tr</span><span class=3D"p">]</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">t</span><span clas=
s=3D"p">([</span><span class=3D"mi">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <spa=
n class=3D"mi">2</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"mi">3</spa=
n><span class=3D"p">])</span>
<span class=3D"go">[1, 2, 3]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>Furthermore, parameterized generics erase type parameters during object
creation:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">t</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <=
span class=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">s=
tr</span><span class=3D"p">]</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">type</span><span =
class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">t</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">&lt;class 'types.GenericAlias'&gt;</span>

<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">l</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"n">t</span><span class=3D"p">()</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">type</span><span =
class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">l</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"go">&lt;class 'list'&gt;</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>Calling <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/library/functions.html#repr" title=3D"repr"><code class=3D"xref py py-fun=
c docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">repr()</span></code></a=
> or <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libr=
ary/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutil=
s literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">str()</span></code></a> on a gen=
eric shows the parameterized type:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">repr</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">i=
nt</span><span class=3D"p">])</span>
<span class=3D"go">'list[int]'</span>

<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">[</span>=
<span class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">])</span>
<span class=3D"go">'list[int]'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/datamodel.html#object.__getitem__" title=3D"object.__getitem__"><co=
de class=3D"xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pr=
e">__getitem__()</span></code></a> method of generic containers will raise =
an
exception to disallow mistakes like <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">dict[str][str]</span></code>:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">dict</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><=
span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">][</span><span class=3D"nb">s=
tr</span><span class=3D"p">]</span>
<span class=3D"gt">Traceback (most recent call last):</span>
<span class=3D"w">  </span><span class=3D"c">...</span>
<span class=3D"gr">TypeError</span>: <span class=3D"n">dict[str] is not a g=
eneric class</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>However, such expressions are valid when <a class=3D"reference internal"=
 href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/typing.html#generics"><span clas=
s=3D"std std-ref">type variables</span></a> are
used.  The index must have as many elements as there are type variable item=
s
in the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Gen=
ericAlias</span></code> object=E2=80=99s <a class=3D"reference internal" hr=
ef=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#genericalias.__args__=
" title=3D"genericalias.__args__"><code class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__args__</span></code></a>.</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-python3 notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"kn">from</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><=
span class=3D"nn">typing</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"kn"=
>import</span> <span class=3D"n">TypeVar</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">Y</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"n">TypeVar</span><span class=3D"p">(</sp=
an><span class=3D"s1">'Y'</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">dict</span><span =
class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">,</span>=
 <span class=3D"n">Y</span><span class=3D"p">][</span><span class=3D"nb">in=
t</span><span class=3D"p">]</span>
<span class=3D"go">dict[str, int]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
