<section id=3D"other-built-in-types">
<span id=3D"typesother"></span><h2>Other Built-in Types<a class=3D"headerli=
nk" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#other-built-in-=
types" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p>The interpreter supports several other kinds of objects. Most of these s=
upport
only one or two operations.</p>
<section id=3D"modules">
<span id=3D"typesmodules"></span><h3>Modules<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#modules" title=3D"Link to =
this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>The only special operation on a module is attribute access: <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">m.name</span></code>,=
 where
<em>m</em> is a module and <em>name</em> accesses a name defined in <em>m</=
em>=E2=80=99s symbol table.
Module attributes can be assigned to.  (Note that the <a class=3D"reference=
 internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/simple_stmts.html#im=
port"><code class=3D"xref std std-keyword docutils literal notranslate"><sp=
an class=3D"pre">import</span></code></a>
statement is not, strictly speaking, an operation on a module object; <code=
 class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">import</span>
<span class=3D"pre">foo</span></code> does not require a module object name=
d <em>foo</em> to exist, rather it requires
an (external) <em>definition</em> for a module named <em>foo</em> somewhere=
.)</p>
<p>A special attribute of every module is <a class=3D"reference internal" h=
ref=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__dict__" =
title=3D"object.__dict__"><code class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal n=
otranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__dict__</span></code></a>. This is the
dictionary containing the module=E2=80=99s symbol table. Modifying this dic=
tionary will
actually change the module=E2=80=99s symbol table, but direct assignment to=
 the
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#object.__dict__" title=3D"object.__dict__"><code class=3D"x=
ref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__dict__</=
span></code></a> attribute is not possible (you can write
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">m.__dict__=
['a']</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">1</span></c=
ode>, which defines <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">m.a</span></code> to be <code class=3D"docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">1</span></code>, but you can=E2=80=99t write
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">m.__dict__=
</span> <span class=3D"pre">=3D</span> <span class=3D"pre">{}</span></code>=
).  Modifying <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.o=
rg/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__dict__" title=3D"object.__dict__"><c=
ode class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">__dict__</span></code></a> directly is
not recommended.</p>
<p>Modules built into the interpreter are written like this: <code class=3D=
"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">&lt;module</span> <span =
class=3D"pre">'sys'</span>
<span class=3D"pre">(built-in)&gt;</span></code>.  If loaded from a file, t=
hey are written as <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">&lt;module</span> <span class=3D"pre">'os'</span> <span class=3D"p=
re">from</span>
<span class=3D"pre">'/usr/local/lib/pythonX.Y/os.pyc'&gt;</span></code>.</p=
>
</section>
<section id=3D"classes-and-class-instances">
<span id=3D"typesobjects"></span><h3>Classes and Class Instances<a class=3D=
"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#classe=
s-and-class-instances" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/datamodel.html#objects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Objects, values=
 and types</span></a> and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://d=
ocs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#class"><span class=3D"std st=
d-ref">Class definitions</span></a> for these.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"functions">
<span id=3D"typesfunctions"></span><h3>Functions<a class=3D"headerlink" hre=
f=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#functions" title=3D"Li=
nk to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>Function objects are created by function definitions.  The only operatio=
n on a
function object is to call it: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"=
><span class=3D"pre">func(argument-list)</span></code>.</p>
<p>There are really two flavors of function objects: built-in functions and
user-defined functions.  Both support the same operation (to call the funct=
ion),
but the implementation is different, hence the different object types.</p>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/compound_stmts.html#function"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Function =
definitions</span></a> for more information.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"methods">
<span id=3D"typesmethods"></span><h3>Methods<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#methods" title=3D"Link to =
this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-62">Methods are functions that are called using the attribut=
e notation.
There are two flavors: <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs=
.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#builtin-methods"><span class=3D"std =
std-ref">built-in methods</span></a>
(such as <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/=
library/stdtypes.html#list.append" title=3D"list.append"><code class=3D"xre=
f py py-meth docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">append()</sp=
an></code></a> on lists)
and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/refer=
ence/datamodel.html#instance-methods"><span class=3D"std std-ref">class ins=
tance method</span></a>.
Built-in methods are described with the types that support them.</p>
<p>If you access a method (a function defined in a class namespace) through=
 an
instance, you get a special object: a <em class=3D"dfn">bound method</em> (=
also called
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#instance-methods"><span class=3D"std std-ref">instance meth=
od</span></a>) object. When called, it will add
the <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">self</=
span></code> argument
to the argument list.  Bound methods have two special read-only attributes:
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#method.__self__" title=3D"method.__self__"><code class=3D"x=
ref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">m.__self__=
</span></code></a> is the object on which the method
operates, and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.o=
rg/3/reference/datamodel.html#method.__func__" title=3D"method.__func__"><c=
ode class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"p=
re">m.__func__</span></code></a> is
the function implementing the method.  Calling <code class=3D"docutils lite=
ral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">m(arg-1,</span> <span class=3D"pre">ar=
g-2,</span> <span class=3D"pre">...,</span> <span class=3D"pre">arg-n)</spa=
n></code>
is completely equivalent to calling <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">m.__func__(m.__self__,</span> <span class=3D"pre"=
>arg-1,</span> <span class=3D"pre">arg-2,</span> <span class=3D"pre">...,</=
span>
<span class=3D"pre">arg-n)</span></code>.</p>
<p>Like <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/r=
eference/datamodel.html#user-defined-funcs"><span class=3D"std std-ref">fun=
ction objects</span></a>, bound method objects support
getting arbitrary
attributes.  However, since method attributes are actually stored on the
underlying function object (<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https:/=
/docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#method.__func__" title=3D"metho=
d.__func__"><code class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">method.__func__</span></code></a>), setting method attrib=
utes on
bound methods is disallowed.  Attempting to set an attribute on a method
results in an <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.o=
rg/3/library/exceptions.html#AttributeError" title=3D"AttributeError"><code=
 class=3D"xref py py-exc docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">=
AttributeError</span></code></a> being raised.  In order to set a method
attribute, you need to explicitly set it on the underlying function object:=
</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-pycon notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"k">class</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><=
span class=3D"nc">C</span><span class=3D"p">:</span>
<span class=3D"gp">... </span>    <span class=3D"k">def</span><span class=
=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"nf">method</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><s=
pan class=3D"bp">self</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
<span class=3D"gp">... </span>        <span class=3D"k">pass</span>
<span class=3D"gp">...</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">c</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"n">C</span><span class=3D"p">()</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">c</span><span clas=
s=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">method</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><s=
pan class=3D"n">whoami</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"s=
1">'my name is method'</span>  <span class=3D"c1"># can't set on the method=
</span>
<span class=3D"gt">Traceback (most recent call last):</span>
  File <span class=3D"nb">"&lt;stdin&gt;"</span>, line <span class=3D"m">1<=
/span>, in <span class=3D"n">&lt;module&gt;</span>
<span class=3D"gr">AttributeError</span>: <span class=3D"n">'method' object=
 has no attribute 'whoami'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">c</span><span clas=
s=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">method</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><s=
pan class=3D"vm">__func__</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n"=
>whoami</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"s1">'my name is =
method'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">c</span><span clas=
s=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">method</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><s=
pan class=3D"n">whoami</span>
<span class=3D"go">'my name is method'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/datamodel.html#instance-methods"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Instan=
ce methods</span></a> for more information.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"code-objects">
<span id=3D"bltin-code-objects"></span><span id=3D"index-63"></span><h3>Cod=
e Objects<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/=
stdtypes.html#code-objects" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-64">Code objects are used by the implementation to represent=
 =E2=80=9Cpseudo-compiled=E2=80=9D
executable Python code such as a function body. They differ from function
objects because they don=E2=80=99t contain a reference to their global exec=
ution
environment.  Code objects are returned by the built-in <a class=3D"referen=
ce internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#compi=
le" title=3D"compile"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">compile()</span></code></a> function
and can be extracted from function objects through their
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#function.__code__" title=3D"function.__code__"><code class=
=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">__cod=
e__</span></code></a> attribute. See also the <a class=3D"reference interna=
l" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/code.html#module-code" title=
=3D"code: Facilities to implement read-eval-print loops."><code class=3D"xr=
ef py py-mod docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">code</span><=
/code></a> module.</p>
<p>Accessing <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.or=
g/3/reference/datamodel.html#function.__code__" title=3D"function.__code__"=
><code class=3D"xref py py-attr docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">__code__</span></code></a> raises an <a class=3D"reference interna=
l" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/sys.html#auditing"><span class=
=3D"std std-ref">auditing event</span></a>
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">object.__g=
etattr__</span></code> with arguments <code class=3D"docutils literal notra=
nslate"><span class=3D"pre">obj</span></code> and <code class=3D"docutils l=
iteral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">"__code__"</span></code>.</p>
<p id=3D"index-65">A code object can be executed or evaluated by passing it=
 (instead of a source
string) to the <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.=
org/3/library/functions.html#exec" title=3D"exec"><code class=3D"xref py py=
-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">exec()</span></code=
></a> or <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/=
library/functions.html#eval" title=3D"eval"><code class=3D"xref py py-func =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">eval()</span></code></a> =
 built-in functions.</p>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/datamodel.html#types"><span class=3D"std std-ref">The standard type=
 hierarchy</span></a> for more information.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"type-objects">
<span id=3D"bltin-type-objects"></span><h3>Type Objects<a class=3D"headerli=
nk" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#type-objects" t=
itle=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p id=3D"index-66">Type objects represent the various object types.  An obj=
ect=E2=80=99s type is accessed
by the built-in function <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://do=
cs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#type" title=3D"type"><code class=3D"=
xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">type()</s=
pan></code></a>.  There are no special operations on
types.  The standard module <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https:/=
/docs.python.org/3/library/types.html#module-types" title=3D"types: Names f=
or built-in types."><code class=3D"xref py py-mod docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">types</span></code></a> defines names for all stan=
dard built-in
types.</p>
<p>Types are written like this: <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate=
"><span class=3D"pre">&lt;class</span> <span class=3D"pre">'int'&gt;</span>=
</code>.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"the-null-object">
<span id=3D"bltin-null-object"></span><h3>The Null Object<a class=3D"header=
link" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#the-null-obje=
ct" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>This object is returned by functions that don=E2=80=99t explicitly retur=
n a value.  It
supports no special operations.  There is exactly one null object, named
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span=
></code> (a built-in name).  <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><=
span class=3D"pre">type(None)()</span></code> produces the same singleton.<=
/p>
<p>It is written as <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">None</span></code>.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"the-ellipsis-object">
<span id=3D"bltin-ellipsis-object"></span><span id=3D"index-67"></span><h3>=
The Ellipsis Object<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/library/stdtypes.html#the-ellipsis-object" title=3D"Link to this heading"=
>=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>This object is commonly used to indicate that something is omitted.
It supports no special operations.  There is exactly one ellipsis object, n=
amed
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/c=
onstants.html#Ellipsis" title=3D"Ellipsis"><code class=3D"xref py py-const =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Ellipsis</span></code></a=
> (a built-in name).  <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span cl=
ass=3D"pre">type(Ellipsis)()</span></code> produces the
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/c=
onstants.html#Ellipsis" title=3D"Ellipsis"><code class=3D"xref py py-const =
docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Ellipsis</span></code></a=
> singleton.</p>
<p>It is written as <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span clas=
s=3D"pre">Ellipsis</span></code> or <code class=3D"docutils literal notrans=
late"><span class=3D"pre">...</span></code>.</p>
<p>In typical use, <code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">...</span></code> as the <code class=3D"docutils literal notransla=
te"><span class=3D"pre">Ellipsis</span></code> object appears in a few diff=
erent
places, for instance:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>In type annotations, such as <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D=
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/typing.html#annotating-callables"><span =
class=3D"std std-ref">callable arguments</span></a>
or <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/typing.html#annotating-tuples"><span class=3D"std std-ref">tuple elements=
</span></a>.</p></li>
<li><p>As the body of a function instead of a <a class=3D"reference interna=
l" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/controlflow.html#tut-pass"><s=
pan class=3D"std std-ref">pass statement</span></a>.</p></li>
<li><p>In third-party libraries, such as <a class=3D"reference external" hr=
ef=3D"https://numpy.org/doc/stable/user/basics.indexing.html#slicing-and-st=
riding">Numpy=E2=80=99s slicing and striding</a>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Python also uses three dots in ways that are not <code class=3D"docutils=
 literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Ellipsis</span></code> objects, f=
or instance:</p>
<ul class=3D"simple">
<li><p>Doctest=E2=80=99s <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://do=
cs.python.org/3/library/doctest.html#doctest.ELLIPSIS" title=3D"doctest.ELL=
IPSIS"><code class=3D"xref py py-const docutils literal notranslate"><span =
class=3D"pre">ELLIPSIS</span></code></a>, as a pattern for missing content.=
</p></li>
<li><p>The default Python prompt of the <a class=3D"reference internal" hre=
f=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-interactive"><span class=
=3D"xref std std-term">interactive</span></a> shell when partial input is i=
ncomplete.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Lastly, the Python documentation often uses three dots in conventional E=
nglish
usage to mean omitted content, even in code examples that also use them as =
the
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">Ellipsis</=
span></code>.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"the-notimplemented-object">
<span id=3D"bltin-notimplemented-object"></span><h3>The NotImplemented Obje=
ct<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtype=
s.html#the-notimplemented-object" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a>=
</h3>
<p>This object is returned from comparisons and binary operations when they=
 are
asked to operate on types they don=E2=80=99t support. See <a class=3D"refer=
ence internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html=
#comparisons"><span class=3D"std std-ref">Comparisons</span></a> for more
information.  There is exactly one <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"=
https://docs.python.org/3/library/constants.html#NotImplemented" title=3D"N=
otImplemented"><code class=3D"xref py py-data docutils literal notranslate"=
><span class=3D"pre">NotImplemented</span></code></a> object.
<code class=3D"code docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">type(=
NotImplemented)()</span></code> produces the singleton instance.</p>
<p>It is written as <code class=3D"code docutils literal notranslate"><span=
 class=3D"pre">NotImplemented</span></code>.</p>
</section>
<section id=3D"internal-objects">
<span id=3D"typesinternal"></span><h3>Internal Objects<a class=3D"headerlin=
k" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#internal-objects=
" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/re=
ference/datamodel.html#types"><span class=3D"std std-ref">The standard type=
 hierarchy</span></a> for this information.  It describes
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#frame-objects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">stack frame obje=
cts</span></a>,
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/reference=
/datamodel.html#traceback-objects"><span class=3D"std std-ref">traceback ob=
jects</span></a>, and slice objects.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"special-attributes">
<span id=3D"specialattrs"></span><h2>Special Attributes<a class=3D"headerli=
nk" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#special-attribu=
tes" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p>The implementation adds a few special read-only attributes to several ob=
ject
types, where they are relevant.  Some of these are not reported by the
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/f=
unctions.html#dir" title=3D"dir"><code class=3D"xref py py-func docutils li=
teral notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">dir()</span></code></a> built-in fun=
ction.</p>
<dl class=3D"py attribute">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"definition.__name__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">definition.</=
span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__name__<=
/span></span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libr=
ary/stdtypes.html#definition.__name__" title=3D"Link to this definition">=
=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>The name of the class, function, method, descriptor, or
generator instance.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py attribute">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"definition.__qualname__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">definition.</=
span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__qualnam=
e__</span></span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/=
library/stdtypes.html#definition.__qualname__" title=3D"Link to this defini=
tion">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/glossary.html#term-qualified-name"><span class=3D"xref std std-term">qual=
ified name</span></a> of the class, function, method, descriptor,
or generator instance.</p>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified added">Added in version 3.3.</span></p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py attribute">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"definition.__module__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">definition.</=
span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__module_=
_</span></span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/li=
brary/stdtypes.html#definition.__module__" title=3D"Link to this definition=
">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>The name of the module in which a class or function was defined.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py attribute">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"definition.__doc__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">definition.</=
span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__doc__</=
span></span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libra=
ry/stdtypes.html#definition.__doc__" title=3D"Link to this definition">=C2=
=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>The documentation string of a class or function, or <code class=3D"d=
ocutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">None</span></code> if unde=
fined.</p>
</dd></dl>

<dl class=3D"py attribute">
<dt class=3D"sig sig-object py" id=3D"definition.__type_params__">
<span class=3D"sig-prename descclassname"><span class=3D"pre">definition.</=
span></span><span class=3D"sig-name descname"><span class=3D"pre">__type_pa=
rams__</span></span><a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org=
/3/library/stdtypes.html#definition.__type_params__" title=3D"Link to this =
definition">=C2=B6</a></dt>
<dd><p>The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/=
3/reference/compound_stmts.html#type-params"><span class=3D"std std-ref">ty=
pe parameters</span></a> of generic classes, functions,
and <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/libra=
ry/typing.html#type-aliases"><span class=3D"std std-ref">type aliases</span=
></a>. For classes and functions that
are not generic, this will be an empty tuple.</p>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
<p><span class=3D"versionmodified added">Added in version 3.12.</span></p>
</div>
</dd></dl>

</section>
<section id=3D"integer-string-conversion-length-limitation">
<span id=3D"int-max-str-digits"></span><h2>Integer string conversion length=
 limitation<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/librar=
y/stdtypes.html#integer-string-conversion-length-limitation" title=3D"Link =
to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h2>
<p>CPython has a global limit for converting between <a class=3D"reference =
internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#int" tit=
le=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><s=
pan class=3D"pre">int</span></code></a> and <a class=3D"reference internal"=
 href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str" title=3D"str"=
><code class=3D"xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate"><span class=
=3D"pre">str</span></code></a>
to mitigate denial of service attacks. This limit <em>only</em> applies to =
decimal or
other non-power-of-two number bases. Hexadecimal, octal, and binary convers=
ions
are unlimited. The limit can be configured.</p>
<p>The <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/li=
brary/functions.html#int" title=3D"int"><code class=3D"xref py py-class doc=
utils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">int</span></code></a> type i=
n CPython is an arbitrary length number stored in binary
form (commonly known as a =E2=80=9Cbignum=E2=80=9D). There exists no algori=
thm that can convert
a string to a binary integer or a binary integer to a string in linear time=
,
<em>unless</em> the base is a power of 2. Even the best known algorithms fo=
r base 10
have sub-quadratic complexity. Converting a large value such as <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">int('1'</span> <span =
class=3D"pre">*</span>
<span class=3D"pre">500_000)</span></code> can take over a second on a fast=
 CPU.</p>
<p>Limiting conversion size offers a practical way to avoid <span class=3D"=
target" id=3D"index-68"></span><a class=3D"cve reference external" href=3D"=
https://www.cve.org/CVERecord?id=3DCVE-2020-10735"><strong>CVE 2020-10735</=
strong></a>.</p>
<p>The limit is applied to the number of digit characters in the input or o=
utput
string when a non-linear conversion algorithm would be involved.  Underscor=
es
and the sign are not counted towards the limit.</p>
<p>When an operation would exceed the limit, a <a class=3D"reference intern=
al" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#ValueError" t=
itle=3D"ValueError"><code class=3D"xref py py-exc docutils literal notransl=
ate"><span class=3D"pre">ValueError</span></code></a> is raised:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-pycon notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"kn">import</span><span class=3D"w"> </span=
><span class=3D"nn">sys</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">sys</span><span cl=
ass=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">set_int_max_str_digits</span><span clas=
s=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"mi">4300</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>  <=
span class=3D"c1"># Illustrative, this is the default.</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">_</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">(</span>=
<span class=3D"s1">'2'</span> <span class=3D"o">*</span> <span class=3D"mi"=
>5432</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"gt">Traceback (most recent call last):</span>
<span class=3D"c">...</span>
<span class=3D"gr">ValueError</span>: <span class=3D"n">Exceeds the limit (=
4300 digits) for integer string conversion: value has 5432 digits; use sys.=
set_int_max_str_digits() to increase the limit</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">i</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">(</span>=
<span class=3D"s1">'2'</span> <span class=3D"o">*</span> <span class=3D"mi"=
>4300</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">len</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"n">i</span><span class=3D"p">))</span>
<span class=3D"go">4300</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">i_squared</span> <=
span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"n">i</span><span class=3D"o">*</=
span><span class=3D"n">i</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">len</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"nb">str</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"n">i_squared</span><span class=3D"p">))</span>
<span class=3D"gt">Traceback (most recent call last):</span>
<span class=3D"c">...</span>
<span class=3D"gr">ValueError</span>: <span class=3D"n">Exceeds the limit (=
4300 digits) for integer string conversion; use sys.set_int_max_str_digits(=
) to increase the limit</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"nb">len</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"nb">hex</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><=
span class=3D"n">i_squared</span><span class=3D"p">))</span>
<span class=3D"go">7144</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"k">assert</span> <spa=
n class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"nb">hex</=
span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">i_squared</span><span clas=
s=3D"p">),</span> <span class=3D"n">base</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span>=
<span class=3D"mi">16</span><span class=3D"p">)</span> <span class=3D"o">=
=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"n">i</span><span class=3D"o">*</span><span cla=
ss=3D"n">i</span>  <span class=3D"c1"># Hexadecimal is unlimited.</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>The default limit is 4300 digits as provided in
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
ys.html#sys.int_info" title=3D"sys.int_info"><code class=3D"xref py py-data=
 docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">sys.int_info.default_max=
_str_digits</span></code></a>.
The lowest limit that can be configured is 640 digits as provided in
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://docs.python.org/3/library/s=
ys.html#sys.int_info" title=3D"sys.int_info"><code class=3D"xref py py-data=
 docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">sys.int_info.str_digits_=
check_threshold</span></code></a>.</p>
<p>Verification:</p>
<div class=3D"highlight-pycon notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight" style=
=3D"position: relative;"><button class=3D"copybutton" type=3D"button" title=
=3D"Copy to clipboard">Copy</button><pre><span></span><span class=3D"gp">&g=
t;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"kn">import</span><span class=3D"w"> </span=
><span class=3D"nn">sys</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"k">assert</span> <spa=
n class=3D"n">sys</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">int_inf=
o</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">default_max_str_digits<=
/span> <span class=3D"o">=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"mi">4300</span><span =
class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"n">sys</span><span class=3D"o">.</span>=
<span class=3D"n">int_info</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"k">assert</span> <spa=
n class=3D"n">sys</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">int_inf=
o</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">str_digits_check_thresh=
old</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D=3D</span> <span class=3D"mi">640</span><sp=
an class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"n">sys</span><span class=3D"o">.</sp=
an><span class=3D"n">int_info</span>
<span class=3D"gp">&gt;&gt;&gt; </span><span class=3D"n">msg</span> <span c=
lass=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"nb">int</span><span class=3D"p">(</spa=
n><span class=3D"s1">'57896629371068288688099403514687379839672225053876276=
1564'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">... </span>          <span class=3D"s1">'925292551438391=
5483333812743580549779436104706260696366600'</span>
<span class=3D"gp">... </span>          <span class=3D"s1">'571186405732'</=
span><span class=3D"p">)</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">=
to_bytes</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"mi">53</span><span =
class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"s1">'big'</span><span class=3D"p">)</sp=
an>
<span class=3D"gp">...</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
